<!-- Hero --------------------------------------------------------------- -->
<section class="hero">
  <div class="inner">
    <span class="eyebrow">Section 05 · GTM</span>
    <h1 class="display">
      How we <span class="accent">find</span> cohort one.
    </h1>
    <p class="lead">
      The strategy, the product, the brand, and the money all point inward — at what we're building. GTM points outward: at the first ten founders who let us run the OS against their growth reality. This section is about how we get there by 29 April, and what we learn from it.
    </p>
  </div>
  <img class="hero-arrow" src="assets/brand-assets/arrow-charcoal.png" alt="">
</section>

<!-- Starting point vs current landing ---------------------------------- -->
<section class="band" style="padding-top: var(--s-8);">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="section-head">
      <span class="eyebrow">The shift</span>
      <h2>From inbound-by-reputation → to a discipline of acquisition.</h2>
      <p class="lead">
        Up to now, client acquisition has been relationship-led — partner networks, referrals, the odd inbound. That's how gritfuel.works reads today: "get in touch, let's talk." Beautiful for the first few clients; invisible as a strategy beyond that. The sprint starts treating GTM as its own discipline, with an explicit assumption-to-tactic chain and a real first cohort.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="themes" style="grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;">
      <div class="theme-card t-strategy" style="min-height: auto;">
        <div class="accent-bar"></div>
        <span class="num">STARTING POINT · today</span>
        <span class="title" style="font-size: 22px;">Relationship-led inbound</span>
        <p class="desc">
          Partner network, referrals, LinkedIn posts when inspiration strikes. Works while we're small and over-indexed on brand equity. No defensible way to forecast next quarter's pipeline.
        </p>
        <p class="desc small" style="color: var(--gray);">Reactive · Opportunistic · Partner-bandwidth-limited</p>
      </div>

      <div class="theme-card t-gtm" style="min-height: auto;">
        <div class="accent-bar"></div>
        <span class="num">CURRENT LANDING · this sprint</span>
        <span class="title" style="font-size: 22px;">Assumption-led outbound + inbound</span>
        <p class="desc">
          Explicit assumptions about who buys, why, when, and through which channel — each mapped to a testable tactic. A first cohort of ~10 founders recruited intentionally, not accidentally. Onboarding flow ready to hit.
        </p>
        <p class="desc small" style="color: var(--gray);">Intentional · Testable · Learning-compounding</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout lime">
      <h4>Cohort one is a learning asset, not a revenue asset</h4>
      <p style="margin:0;">
        The first ten aren't priced to maximise revenue — they're priced to maximise what we learn about delivery, tooling, escalation, and positioning. Every assumption in the map gets tested through them. That framing matters for how we recruit and what we promise.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- Narrative ---------------------------------------------------------- -->
<section class="band" style="padding-top: 0;">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="section-head">
      <span class="eyebrow">From assumption to tactic</span>
      <h2>Ten assumptions, ten tactics, one cohort.</h2>
      <p class="lead">
        The Assumption-to-Tactic map is the spine. Each assumption (e.g. "post-seed founders will pay monthly for a system, not a service") has a tactic ("targeted outbound to founders of €1m – €5m revenue consumer DTCs; pitch the Playbook not the team") and a falsifier ("if conversion to discovery call is under 8% across 100 attempts, the assumption is wrong").
      </p>
      <p>
        Cohort one runs across the first 90 days post go-live. By July we'll know which assumptions held, which broke, and which we mis-specified.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Key decisions -->
    <div class="section-head" style="margin-top: var(--s-8);">
      <span class="eyebrow">Key decisions</span>
      <h2>What's locked, what's open.</h2>
    </div>

    <div class="decisions">
      <div class="decision locked">
        <div class="marker"></div>
        <div class="body">
          <h4>Cohort-one framing — learning cohort, not revenue cohort</h4>
          <p>First ten clients are priced, scoped, and recruited to maximise signal. We say that to them openly. It makes partner conversations easier.</p>
        </div>
        <span class="status">Locked</span>
      </div>
      <div class="decision locked">
        <div class="marker"></div>
        <div class="body">
          <h4>Assumption-to-tactic map as the GTM operating doc</h4>
          <p>Every tactic has an assumption behind it and a falsifier. No un-attributed activity. Updated monthly based on cohort-one signal.</p>
        </div>
        <span class="status">Locked</span>
      </div>
      <div class="decision open">
        <div class="marker"></div>
        <div class="body">
          <h4>Channel weighting — outbound, inbound, or partner-led for cohort one?</h4>
          <p>All three work. The question is where we spend scarce founder-time. My read: 60% outbound, 30% partner-led, 10% content inbound. Push back.</p>
        </div>
        <span class="status">Open</span>
      </div>
      <div class="decision open">
        <div class="marker"></div>
        <div class="body">
          <h4>Who runs outbound — us, or an external partner?</h4>
          <p>Cohort-one outbound will eat hours. Options: a partner rotates in; we hire a junior BDR on day one; we use an outbound partner on a results-only arrangement. All three have costs.</p>
        </div>
        <span class="status">Open</span>
      </div>
      <div class="decision open">
        <div class="marker"></div>
        <div class="body">
          <h4>Onboarding flow — founder-only or founder + team?</h4>
          <p>The Onboarding Intake is written for the founder. Most of our target companies have a head of growth or head of marketing too. Do we insist on both being in the intake, or keep it founder-only and invite the team in post-signature?</p>
        </div>
        <span class="status">Open</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- Artefacts ---------------------------------------------------------- -->
<section class="band dark" style="padding-top: var(--s-8); padding-bottom: var(--s-8);">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="section-head">
      <span class="eyebrow">The artefacts</span>
      <h2>Three reads, one hour.</h2>
      <p>The Assumption-to-Tactic map is the core doc. The PMF note is the why behind the positioning. The Onboarding Intake (also linked from Product) is the front door.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="artefacts">

      <!-- Assumption tactics -->
      <article class="artefact">
        <span class="tag html">HTML · Map</span>
        <h3>Assumption-to-Tactic Map</h3>
        <p class="desc">The ten core assumptions behind the GTM plan, each with a tactic, a metric, and a falsifier. The single doc I'd print and put on the wall.</p>
        <p class="look"><strong>Look at:</strong> assumption #4 (channel economics) — that's the one most likely to be wrong.</p>
        <div class="links">
          <a class="btn" href="artefacts/GritFuel_Assumption_Tactics_v1.html" target="_blank">Open map →</a>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- PMF assessment (also in strategy) -->
      <article class="artefact">
        <span class="tag doc">DOCX · Positioning note</span>
        <h3>PMF Assessment &amp; Positioning Recommendations</h3>
        <p class="desc">Same file referenced in Strategy. Included here because Section 3 — positioning recommendations — directly drives cohort-one outbound messaging.</p>
        <p class="look"><strong>Look at:</strong> section 3 specifically. The rest is context.</p>
        <div class="links">
          <a class="btn ghost" href="downloads/GritFuel — PMF Assessment &amp; Positioning Recommendations.docx" download>Download .docx</a>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- Onboarding intake -->
      <article class="artefact">
        <span class="tag html">HTML · Flow</span>
        <h3>Onboarding Intake (front door)</h3>
        <p class="desc">The flow a new founder walks through the first time they engage. Produces the brief the rest of the OS runs off. Same tool referenced in Product — included here because it <em>is</em> the GTM conversion surface.</p>
        <p class="look"><strong>Look at:</strong> whether the first three questions earn the trust required to ask the later, harder ones.</p>
        <div class="links">
          <a class="btn" href="artefacts/Tool_01_Onboarding_Intake.html" target="_blank">Open flow →</a>
        </div>
      </article>

    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- Asks --------------------------------------------------------------- -->
<section class="band" style="padding-top: var(--s-8);">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="asks">
      <span class="eyebrow" style="color: var(--lime);">What I need from you</span>
      <h3>Three specific questions on GTM.</h3>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Channel weighting:</strong> is my 60/30/10 split (outbound / partner-led / content inbound) for cohort one the right shape? If not — what moves?</li>
        <li><strong>Outbound ownership:</strong> a partner rotates in, we hire a junior BDR, or we use an outbound partner on results-only? Each has a cost the group has to accept.</li>
        <li><strong>Intake participants:</strong> founder-only (simpler, faster) or founder + growth lead (more work to schedule, better brief)?</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

